n University of Technology, Xiamen, China 3. Fujian Key Lab of Medical Instrumentation & Pharmaceutical Technology, Fuzhou, China 3. Fujian Key Lab of Medical Instrumentation & Pharmaceutical Technology, Fuzhou, China 4. Imperial Vision Technology, Fuzhou, China 4. Imperial Vision Technology, Fuzhou, China 5. School of Computer & Information Engineering, Xiamen University of Technology, Xiamen, China 5. School of Computer & Information Engineering, Xiamen University of Technology, Xiamen, China 6. Department of Radiology, Xiamen 2nd Hospital, Xiamen, China 6. Department of Radiology, Xiamen 2nd Hospital, Xiamen, China 7. Fujian Provincial Key Laboratory of Eco-Industrial Green Technology, Nanping, China 7. Fujian Provincial Key Laboratory of Eco-Industrial Green Technology, Nanping, China 8. Department of Electronic Science, Xiamen University, Xiamen, China 8. Department of Electronic Science, Xiamen University, Xiamen, China Mild cognitive impairment (MCI) is the prodromal stage of Alzheimer’s disease (AD). Identifying MCI subjects who are at high risk of converting to AD is crucial for effective treatments. In this study, a deep learning approach based on convolutional neural networks (CNN), is designed to accurately predict MCI-to-AD conversion with magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) data. First, MRI images are prepared with age-correction and other processing. Second, local patches, which are assembled into 2.5 dimensions, are extracted from these images. Then, the patches from AD and normal controls (NC) are used to train a CNN to identify deep learning features of MCI subjects. After that, structural brain image features are mined with FreeSurfer to assist CNN. Finally, both types of features are fed into an extreme learning machine classifier to predict the AD conversion. The proposed approach is validated on the standardized MRI datasets from the Alzheimer’s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) project. This approach achieves an accuracy of 79.9% and an area